1. User opens your page in Flip iFrame
        ↓
2. No session → frontend redirects to Keycloak
   (Keycloak = Flip's login server)
   URL: https://straightforward.flip-app.com/auth/realms/.../auth
        ?client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID
        &redirect_uri=https://your-domain.com/mitarbeiter/einsaetze
        &response_type=code
        &scope=openid email
        &prompt=none        ← "silent" — user already logged into Flip, no login screen shown
        ↓
3. Keycloak sees the user is already logged in → redirects back:
   https://your-domain.com/mitarbeiter/einsaetze?code=abc123
        ↓
4. Frontend sends code to YOUR backend:
   POST /api/oidc/callback
   { code: "abc123", code_verifier: "...", redirect_uri: "..." }
        ↓
5. YOUR backend calls Keycloak token endpoint:
   POST https://.../token  { code, client_id, code_verifier }
   ← Keycloak returns an ID token (signed JWT)
        ↓
6. YOUR backend verifies the ID token signature using Keycloak's public keys
   (fetched automatically from JWKS URI — no extra config needed)
   → extracts email from the token
        ↓
7. YOUR backend issues its own short-lived session JWT (12 hours):
   { email: "user@example.com", source: "oidc" }  signed with JWT_SECRET
        ↓
8. Frontend stores session JWT in sessionStorage
   → loads /api/public/mitarbeiter?email=... with that JWT as token
   → works exactly like before, but the email is now cryptographically verified